  "prompt": "How do I give my girlfriend space / stop the feeling of having my soul sucked out for the seconds I'm not with her?",
  "response": "Okay, it sounds like you're experiencing a strong pull towards your girlfriend, to the point where you feel depleted when you're apart. That's a common feeling, especially in new or intense relationships, but it's important to address it for your own well-being and the health of the relationship. Here's a breakdown of how to give her space and reclaim your own sense of self:\n\n**1. Understand Why You Feel This Way:**\n\n*   **Attachment Style:** Consider exploring attachment styles. Are you leaning towards an anxious attachment style? People with anxious attachment often crave closeness and fear abandonment. Understanding your attachment style can help you understand your needs and behaviors.\n*   **Insecurity:** Are you feeling insecure about the relationship? Fear of her leaving, not being good enough, or competition from others?\n*   **Lack of Identity Outside the Relationship:** Has your relationship become the primary focus of your life? Have you neglected your hobbies, friendships, and personal goals?\n*   **Codependency:** Are you relying on her happiness for your own? Are you constantly trying to fix her problems or please her at the expense of your own needs?\n*   **Past Experiences:** Past relationship trauma (abandonment, betrayal) can contribute to heightened anxiety when you're apart from your partner.\n\n**2. Practical Steps to Create Space (Gradually):**\n\n*   **Schedule \"Me Time\":** This is crucial. Block out specific times in your week for activities that are just for you. This could be reading, gaming, exercising, pursuing a hobby, or simply relaxing alone.  Treat these appointments as seriously as you would any other important commitment.\n*   **Reconnect with Friends and Family:** Nurture your relationships outside of the romantic one. Make plans with friends, call your family members, and invest time in those connections.\n*   **Communicate Your Needs (Calmly and Clearly):** Don't spring it on her.  Find a good time to talk to your girlfriend about your need for more individual time.  Use \"I\" statements:\n    *   \"I've been feeling like I need to reconnect with some of my hobbies.\"\n    *   \"I'm realizing that having more individual time will help me feel more balanced.\"\n    *   \"I value our relationship, and I also need to make sure I'm taking care of myself.\"\n    *   **Avoid Blame:** Don't say things like \"You're suffocating me\" or \"You need to give me more space.\"\n*   **Set Realistic Expectations:** Don't go from constant contact to complete silence overnight. Gradual changes are easier to adjust to. Maybe start by having one or two evenings a week where you don't text or call each other.\n*   **Avoid \"Checking In\" Excessively:** Resist the urge to constantly text or call her when you're apart. Trust that she's okay and that she'll reach out if she needs you.\n*   **Be Present When You Are Together:** When you *are* with her, be fully present and engaged. Put away your phone, listen attentively, and enjoy the time together. This will make the time apart feel less like a deprivation.\n*   **Plan Separate Activities:** Suggest activities that you each enjoy independently.  Maybe she goes to a yoga class while you go rock climbing.  Then you can come back together and share your experiences.\n\n**3. Shifting Your Mindset:**\n\n*   **Focus on the Benefits of Space:** Remind yourself that having individual time will make you a happier, more well-rounded person, which will ultimately benefit the relationship.  Think about how your hobbies and friendships enrich your life.\n*   **Challenge Negative Thoughts:** When you start to feel anxious about being apart from her, challenge those thoughts. Ask yourself:\n    *   Is this thought based on facts or feelings?\n    *   What's the worst that could happen if I don't contact her right now?\n    *   What evidence do I have that she doesn't care about me?\n    *   What would I tell a friend who was feeling this way?\n*   **Practice Self-Care:** Prioritize your physical and mental health. Get enough sleep, eat healthy foods, exercise regularly, and practice mindfulness or meditation.\n*   **Build Self-Esteem:** Work on your self-confidence. Remind yourself of your strengths and accomplishments. Focus on things you're good at and that make you feel good about yourself.\n*   **Embrace the Unknown:** Part of the joy of a relationship is the anticipation of seeing each other again. Don't try to control every moment. Trust that things will unfold naturally.\n*   **Gratitude:** Focus on what you have, not what you lack. Be grateful for your relationship, but also for the other good things in your life.\n\n**4. Consider Professional Help:**\n\n*   **Therapy:** If you're struggling to manage your anxiety or codependency on your own, consider seeking therapy. A therapist can help you identify the underlying causes of your feelings and develop healthy coping mechanisms.  Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) and Attachment-Based Therapy can be particularly helpful.\n\n**Important Considerations for Your Girlfriend:**\n\n*   **Don't Make Her Responsible for Your Feelings:** It's important to take ownership of your own emotions and not put the burden on her to constantly reassure you.\n*   **Be Patient:** It may take time for her to adjust to the changes in your dynamic.\n*   **Be Respectful of Her Needs:** She may have her own needs for space and independence, so be open to communicating about those as well.\n*   **Reassure Her:** Let her know that needing space doesn't mean you love her any less.\n\n**In summary, giving your girlfriend space is about creating a healthy balance in your life and relationship. It's about reclaiming your own identity, pursuing your passions, and trusting that your relationship can thrive even when you're not constantly together. It takes conscious effort and communication, but the rewards of a more balanced and fulfilling life are well worth it.**\n",
